[src:thiserror-rust/code-generation-compiler] In computing, **code generation** is part of the process chain of a compiler, in which an intermediate representation of source code is converted into a form (e.g., machine code) that the target system can readily execute.
[src:thiserror-rust/code-generation-compiler] Sophisticated compilers typically perform multiple passes over various intermediate forms.
[src:thiserror-rust/code-generation-compiler] This multi-stage process is used because many algorithms for code optimization are easier to apply one at a time, or because the input to one optimization relies on the completed processing performed by another optimization.
[src:thiserror-rust/code-generation-compiler] This organization also facilitates the creation of a single compiler that can target multiple architectures, as only the last of the code generation stages (the *backend*) needs to change from target to target.
[src:thiserror-rust/code-generation-compiler] The input to the code generator typically consists of a parse tree or an abstract syntax tree.
[src:thiserror-rust/code-generation-compiler] The tree is converted into a linear sequence of instructions, usually in an intermediate language such as three-address code.
[src:thiserror-rust/code-generation-compiler] Further stages of compilation may or may not be referred to as "code generation", depending on whether they involve a significant change in the representation of the program.
[src:thiserror-rust/code-generation-compiler] In addition to converting an intermediate representation into a linear sequence of machine instructions, a typical code generator tries to optimize the generated code.
[src:thiserror-rust/code-generation-compiler] In a compiler that uses an intermediate language, there may be two instruction selection stages—one to convert the parse tree into intermediate code, and a second phase, much later, to convert the intermediate code into instructions from the instruction set of the target machine.
[src:thiserror-rust/code-generation-compiler] This second phase does not require a tree traversal; it can be done linearly, and typically involves a simple replacement of intermediate-language operations with their corresponding opcodes.
[src:thiserror-rust/code-generation-compiler] However, suppose the compiler is a language translator (for example, one that converts Java to C++).
[src:thiserror-rust/code-generation-compiler] In that case, the second code-generation phase may involve *building* a tree from the linear intermediate code.
[src:thiserror-rust/code-generation-compiler] When code generation occurs at runtime, as in just-in-time compilation (JIT), the entire process must be efficient with respect to space and time.
[src:thiserror-rust/code-generation-compiler] For example, when regular expressions are interpreted and used to generate code at runtime, a non-deterministic finite-state machine is often generated instead of a deterministic one because the former can usually be created more quickly and occupies less memory space than the latter.
[src:thiserror-rust/code-generation-compiler] Despite generally generating less efficient code, JIT code generation can take advantage of profiling information that is available only at runtime.
[src:thiserror-rust/code-generation-compiler] The fundamental task of taking input in one language and producing output in a non-trivially different language can be understood in terms of the core transformational operations of formal language theory.
[src:thiserror-rust/code-generation-compiler] Consequently, some techniques initially developed for use in compilers have come to be employed in other ways.
[src:thiserror-rust/code-generation-compiler] For example, YACC (Yet Another Compiler-Compiler) takes input in Backus–Naur form and converts it to a parser in C.
[src:thiserror-rust/code-generation-compiler] Though it was initially created for automatic generation of a parser for a compiler, yacc is also often used to automate writing code that needs to be modified each time specifications are changed.
[src:thiserror-rust/code-generation-compiler] Many integrated development environments (IDEs) support some form of automatic source-code generation, often using algorithms in common with compiler code generators, although commonly less complicated.
[src:thiserror-rust/code-generation-compiler] In general, a syntax and semantic analyzer tries to retrieve the program's structure from the source code, while a code generator uses this structural information (e.g., data types) to produce code.
[src:thiserror-rust/code-generation-compiler] In other words, the former *adds* information while the latter *loses* some.
[src:thiserror-rust/code-generation-compiler] One consequence of this information loss is that reflection becomes difficult or even impossible.
[src:thiserror-rust/code-generation-compiler] To counter this problem, code generators often embed syntactic and semantic information and the code necessary for execution.
[src:thiserror-rust/exception-handling] In computing and computer programming, **exception handling** is the process of responding to the occurrence of *exceptions* – anomalous or exceptional conditions requiring special processing – during the execution of a program.
[src:thiserror-rust/exception-handling] In general, an exception breaks the normal flow of execution and executes a pre-registered *exception handler*; the details of how this is done depend on whether it is a hardware or software exception and how the software exception is implemented.
[src:thiserror-rust/exception-handling] Exceptions are defined by different layers of a computer system, and the typical layers are CPU-defined interrupts, operating system (OS)-defined signals, and programming language-defined exceptions.
[src:thiserror-rust/exception-handling] Each layer requires different ways of exception handling although they may be interrelated, e.g. a CPU interrupt could be turned into an OS signal.
[src:thiserror-rust/exception-handling] Some exceptions, especially hardware ones, may be handled so gracefully that execution can resume where it was interrupted.
[src:thiserror-rust/exception-handling] The definition of an exception is based on the observation that each procedure has a precondition, a set of circumstances for which it will terminate "normally".
[src:thiserror-rust/exception-handling] An exception handling mechanism allows the procedure to *raise an exception* if this precondition is violated, for example if the procedure has been called on an abnormal set of arguments.
[src:thiserror-rust/exception-handling] The exception handling mechanism then *handles* the exception.
[src:thiserror-rust/exception-handling] The precondition, and the definition of exception, is subjective.
[src:thiserror-rust/exception-handling] The set of "normal" circumstances is defined entirely by the programmer, e.g. the programmer may deem division by zero to be undefined, hence an exception, or devise some behavior such as returning zero or a special "ZERO DIVIDE" value (circumventing the need for exceptions).
[src:thiserror-rust/exception-handling] Social pressure is a major influence on the scope of exceptions and use of exception-handling mechanisms, i.e.
[src:thiserror-rust/exception-handling] "examples of use, typically found in core libraries, and code examples in technical books, magazine articles, and online discussion forums, and in an organization’s code standards".
[src:thiserror-rust/exception-handling] Exception handling solves the semipredicate problem, in that the mechanism distinguishes normal return values from erroneous ones.
[src:thiserror-rust/exception-handling] In languages without built-in exception handling such as C, routines would need to signal the error in some other way, such as the common return code and errno pattern.
[src:thiserror-rust/exception-handling] Taking a broad view, errors can be considered to be a proper subset of exceptions, and explicit error mechanisms such as errno can be considered (verbose) forms of exception handling.
[src:thiserror-rust/exception-handling] The term "exception" is preferred to "error" because it does not imply that anything is wrong - a condition viewed as an error by one procedure or programmer may not be viewed that way by another.
[src:thiserror-rust/exception-handling] The term "exception" may be misleading because its connotation of "anomaly" indicates that raising an exception is abnormal or unusual, when in fact raising the exception may be a normal and usual situation in the program.
[src:thiserror-rust/exception-handling] For example, suppose a lookup function for an associative array throws an exception if the key has no value associated.
[src:thiserror-rust/exception-handling] Depending on context, this "key absent" exception may occur much more often than a successful lookup.
[src:thiserror-rust/exception-handling] The first hardware exception handling was found in the UNIVAC I from 1951.
[src:thiserror-rust/exception-handling] Arithmetic overflow executed two instructions at address 0 which could transfer control or fix up the result.
[src:thiserror-rust/exception-handling] Software exception handling developed in the 1960s and 1970s.
[src:thiserror-rust/exception-handling] Exception handling was subsequently widely adopted by many programming languages from the 1980s onward.
[src:thiserror-rust/exception-handling] There is no clear consensus as to the exact meaning of an exception with respect to hardware.
[src:thiserror-rust/exception-handling] From the implementation point of view, it is handled identically to an interrupt: the processor halts execution of the current program, looks up the interrupt handler in the interrupt vector table for that exception or interrupt condition, saves state, and switches control.
[src:thiserror-rust/exception-handling] Exception handling in the IEEE 754 floating-point standard refers in general to exceptional conditions and defines an exception as "an event that occurs when an operation on some particular operands has no outcome suitable for every reasonable application.
[src:thiserror-rust/exception-handling] An exception-handling style enabled by the use of status flags involves: first computing an expression using a fast, direct implementation; checking whether it failed by testing status flags; and then, if necessary, calling a slower, more numerically robust, implementation.
[src:thiserror-rust/exception-handling] The IEEE 754 standard uses the term "trapping" to refer to the calling of a user-supplied exception-handling routine on exceptional conditions, and is an optional feature of the standard.
[src:thiserror-rust/exception-handling] The standard recommends several usage scenarios for this, including the implementation of non-default pre-substitution of a value followed by resumption, to concisely handle removable singularities.
[src:thiserror-rust/exception-handling] The default IEEE 754 exception handling behaviour of resumption following pre-substitution of a default value avoids the risks inherent in changing flow of program control on numerical exceptions.
[src:thiserror-rust/exception-handling] For example, the 1996 Cluster spacecraft launch ended in a catastrophic explosion due in part to the Ada exception handling policy of aborting computation on arithmetic error.
[src:thiserror-rust/exception-handling] William Kahan claims the default IEEE 754 exception handling behavior would have prevented this.
[src:thiserror-rust/exception-handling] In computer programming, several programming language mechanisms exist for exception handling.
[src:thiserror-rust/exception-handling] The term *exception* is typically used to denote a data structure storing information about an exceptional condition.
[src:thiserror-rust/exception-handling] One mechanism to transfer control, or *raise* an exception, is known as a *throw*; the exception is said to be *thrown*.
[src:thiserror-rust/exception-handling] Front-end web development frameworks, such as React and Vue, have introduced error handling mechanisms where errors propagate up the user interface (UI) component hierarchy, in a way that is analogous to how errors propagate up the call stack in executing code.
[src:thiserror-rust/exception-handling] Here the error boundary mechanism serves as an analogue to the typical try-catch mechanism.
[src:thiserror-rust/exception-handling] Thus a component can ensure that errors from its child components are caught and handled, and not propagated up to parent components.
[src:thiserror-rust/exception-handling] The error produced by the child component is caught and handled by the parent component.
[src:thiserror-rust/latest-thiserror] This library provides a convenient derive macro for the standard library’s `std::error::Error` trait.
[src:thiserror-rust/metaprogramming] Metaprogramming can be used to move computations from runtime to compile time, to generate code using compile time computations, and to enable self-modifying code.
[src:thiserror-rust/metaprogramming] The ability of a programming language to be its own metalanguage allows reflective programming, and is termed *reflection*.
[src:thiserror-rust/metaprogramming] Reflection is a valuable language feature to facilitate metaprogramming.
[src:thiserror-rust/metaprogramming] Metaprogramming was popular in the 1970s and 1980s using list processing languages such as Lisp.
[src:thiserror-rust/metaprogramming] Lisp machine hardware gained some notice in the 1980s, and enabled applications that could process code.
[src:thiserror-rust/metaprogramming] They were often used for artificial intelligence applications.
[src:thiserror-rust/metaprogramming] Metaprogramming enables developers to write programs and develop code that falls under the generic programming paradigm.
[src:thiserror-rust/metaprogramming] Having the programming language itself as a first-class data type (as in Lisp, Prolog, SNOBOL, or Rebol) is also very useful; this is known as *homoiconicity*.
[src:thiserror-rust/metaprogramming] Generic programming invokes a metaprogramming facility within a language by allowing one to write code without the concern of specifying data types since they can be supplied as parameters when used.
[src:thiserror-rust/metaprogramming] Metaprogramming usually works in one of three ways.
[src:thiserror-rust/metaprogramming] The second approach is dynamic execution of expressions that contain programming commands, often composed from strings, but can also be from other methods using arguments or context, like JavaScript.
[src:thiserror-rust/metaprogramming] Thus, "programs can write programs." Although both approaches can be used in the same language, most languages tend to lean toward one or the other.
[src:thiserror-rust/metaprogramming] The third approach is to step outside the language entirely.
[src:thiserror-rust/metaprogramming] General purpose program transformation systems such as compilers, which accept language descriptions and carry out arbitrary transformations on those languages, are direct implementations of general metaprogramming.
[src:thiserror-rust/metaprogramming] This allows metaprogramming to be applied to virtually any target language without regard to whether that target language has any metaprogramming abilities of its own.
[src:thiserror-rust/metaprogramming] One can see this at work with Scheme and how it allows tackling some limits faced in C by using constructs that are part of the Scheme language to extend C.
[src:thiserror-rust/metaprogramming] Lisp is probably the quintessential language with metaprogramming facilities, both because of its historical precedence and because of the simplicity and power of its metaprogramming.
[src:thiserror-rust/metaprogramming] In Lisp metaprogramming, the unquote operator (typically a comma) introduces code that is evaluated at program definition time rather than at run time.
[src:thiserror-rust/metaprogramming] The metaprogramming language is thus identical to the host programming language, and existing Lisp routines can be directly reused for metaprogramming if desired.
[src:thiserror-rust/metaprogramming] This approach has been implemented in other languages by incorporating an interpreter in the program, which works directly with the program's data.
[src:thiserror-rust/metaprogramming] There are implementations of this kind for some common high-level languages, such as RemObjects’ Pascal Script for Object Pascal.
[src:thiserror-rust/metaprogramming] This script (or program) generates a new 993-line program that prints out the numbers 1–992.
[src:thiserror-rust/metaprogramming] This is only an illustration of how to use code to write more code; it is not the most efficient way to print out a list of numbers.
[src:thiserror-rust/metaprogramming] Nonetheless, a programmer can write and execute this metaprogram in less than a minute, and will have generated over 1000 lines of code in that amount of time.
[src:thiserror-rust/metaprogramming] A quine is a special kind of metaprogram that produces its own source code as its output.
[src:thiserror-rust/metaprogramming] Quines are generally of recreational or theoretical interest only.
[src:thiserror-rust/metaprogramming] Not all metaprogramming involves generative programming.
[src:thiserror-rust/metaprogramming] One style of generative approach is to employ domain-specific languages (DSLs).
[src:thiserror-rust/metaprogramming] One usage of metaprogramming is to instrument programs in order to do dynamic program analysis.
[src:thiserror-rust/metaprogramming] Some argue that there is a sharp learning curve to make complete use of metaprogramming features.
[src:thiserror-rust/metaprogramming] Since metaprogramming gives more flexibility and configurability at runtime, misuse or incorrect use of metaprogramming can result in unwarranted and unexpected errors that can be extremely difficult to debug to an average developer.
[src:thiserror-rust/metaprogramming] It can introduce risks in the system and make it more vulnerable if not used with care.
[src:thiserror-rust/metaprogramming] Some of the common problems, which can occur due to wrong use of metaprogramming are inability of the compiler to identify missing configuration parameters, invalid or incorrect data can result in unknown exception or different results.
[src:thiserror-rust/metaprogramming] Due to this, some believe that only high-skilled developers should work on developing features which exercise metaprogramming in a language or platform and average developers must learn how to use these features as part of convention.
[src:thiserror-rust/metaprogramming] The IBM/360 and derivatives had powerful macro assembler facilities that were often used to generate complete assembly language programs or sections of programs (for different operating systems for instance).
[src:thiserror-rust/metaprogramming] Macros provided with CICS transaction processing system had assembler macros that generated COBOL statements as a pre-processing step.
[src:thiserror-rust/metaprogramming] Other assemblers, such as MASM, also support macros.
[src:thiserror-rust/metaprogramming] Use of dependent types allows proving that generated code is never invalid.
[src:thiserror-rust/metaprogramming] However, this approach is leading-edge and rarely found outside of research programming languages.
[src:thiserror-rust/metaprogramming] The list of notable metaprogramming systems is maintained at List of program transformation systems.
[src:thiserror-rust/result-type] In functional programming, a **result type** is a monadic type holding a returned value or an error code.
[src:thiserror-rust/result-type] The `expected<T, E>` class uses `std::unexpected()` to return the type `E`, and can return `T` directly.
[src:thiserror-rust/result-type] Enums in Rust are tagged unions, which can be unpacked with strong type checking through pattern matching.
[src:thiserror-rust/result-type] The `Error` type is an interface for `iError`.
[src:thiserror-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust supports multiple programming paradigms.
[src:thiserror-rust/rust-programming-language] It was influenced by ideas from functional programming, including immutability, higher-order functions, algebraic data types, and pattern matching.
[src:thiserror-rust/rust-programming-language] It also supports object-oriented programming via structs, enums, traits, and methods.
[src:thiserror-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust enforces memory safety (i.e., that all references point to valid memory) without a conventional garbage collector; instead, memory safety errors and data races are prevented by the "borrow checker", which tracks the object lifetime of references at compile time.
[src:thiserror-rust/rust-programming-language] Software developer Graydon Hoare created Rust in 2006 while working at Mozilla, which officially sponsored the project in 2009.
[src:thiserror-rust/rust-programming-language] The first stable release, Rust 1.0, was published in May 2015.
[src:thiserror-rust/rust-programming-language] The project has been sponsored by the Rust Foundation since February 2021.
[src:thiserror-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust has been adopted by many software projects, especially web services and system software.
[src:thiserror-rust/rust-programming-language] It has been studied academically and has a growing community of developers.
[src:thiserror-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust began as a personal project by Mozilla employee Graydon Hoare in 2006.
[src:thiserror-rust/rust-programming-language] According to *MIT Technology Review*, he started the project due to his frustration with a broken elevator in his apartment building whose software had crashed, and named the language after the group of fungi of the same name that is "over-engineered for survival".
[src:thiserror-rust/rust-programming-language] During the time period between 2006 and 2009, Rust was not publicized to others at Mozilla and was written in Hoare's free time; Hoare began speaking about the language around 2009 after a small group at Mozilla became interested in the project.
[src:thiserror-rust/rust-programming-language] Hoare cited languages from the 1970s, 1980s, and 1990s as influences — including CLU, BETA, Mesa, NIL, Erlang, Newsqueak, Napier, Hermes, Sather, Alef, and Limbo.
[src:thiserror-rust/rust-programming-language] During the early years, the Rust compiler was written in about 38,000 lines of OCaml.
[src:thiserror-rust/rust-programming-language] Early Rust contained several features no longer present today, including explicit object-oriented programming via an `obj` keyword and a typestates system for variable state changes, such as going from uninitialized to initialized.
[src:thiserror-rust/rust-programming-language] Mozilla officially sponsored the Rust project in 2009.
[src:thiserror-rust/rust-programming-language] Brendan Eich and other executives, intrigued by the possibility of using Rust for a safe web browser engine, placed engineers on the project including Patrick Walton, Niko Matsakis, Felix Klock, and Manish Goregaokar.
[src:thiserror-rust/rust-programming-language] A conference room taken by the project developers was dubbed "the nerd cave," with a sign placed outside the door.
[src:thiserror-rust/rust-programming-language] During this time period, work had shifted from the initial OCaml compiler to a self-hosting compiler (*i.e.*, written in Rust) targeting LLVM.
[src:thiserror-rust/rust-programming-language] The ownership system was in place by 2010.
[src:thiserror-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust logo was developed in 2011 based on a bicycle chainring.
[src:thiserror-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust 0.1 became the first public release on January 20, 2012 for Windows, Linux, and MacOS.
[src:thiserror-rust/rust-programming-language] The early 2010s witnessed increasing involvement from full-time engineers at Mozilla and open source volunteers outside Mozilla.
[src:thiserror-rust/rust-programming-language] The years from 2012 to 2015 were marked by substantial changes to the Rust type system.
[src:thiserror-rust/rust-programming-language] Memory management through the ownership system was gradually consolidated and expanded.
[src:thiserror-rust/rust-programming-language] By 2013, the garbage collector was rarely used, and was removed in favor of the ownership system.
[src:thiserror-rust/rust-programming-language] Other features were removed in order to simplify the language, including typestates, the `pure` keyword, various specialized pointer types, and syntax support for channels.
[src:thiserror-rust/rust-programming-language] According to Steve Klabnik, Rust was influenced during this period by developers coming from C++ (e.g., low-level performance of features), scripting languages (e.g., Cargo and package management), and functional programming (e.g., type systems development).
[src:thiserror-rust/rust-programming-language] Graydon Hoare stepped down from Rust in 2013.
[src:thiserror-rust/rust-programming-language] After Hoare's departure, it evolved organically under a federated governance structure, with a "core team" of initially six people, and around 30-40 developers total across various other teams.
[src:thiserror-rust/rust-programming-language] A Request for Comments (RFC) process for new language features was added in March 2014.
[src:thiserror-rust/rust-programming-language] The core team would grow to nine people by 2016 with over 1600 RFCs.
[src:thiserror-rust/rust-programming-language] Dobb's Journal* in January 2014, while Rust was "widely viewed as a remarkably elegant language", adoption slowed because it radically changed from version to version.
[src:thiserror-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust development at this time focused on finalizing features for version 1.0 so that it could begin promising backward compatibility.
[src:thiserror-rust/rust-programming-language] Six years after Mozilla's sponsorship, Rust 1.0 was published and became the first stable release on May 15, 2015.
[src:thiserror-rust/rust-programming-language] A year later, the Rust compiler had accumulated over 1,400 contributors, and there were over 5,000 third-party libraries published on the Rust package management website Crates.io.
[src:thiserror-rust/rust-programming-language] The development of the Servo browser engine continued in parallel with Rust, jointly funded by Mozilla and Samsung.
[src:thiserror-rust/rust-programming-language] The teams behind the two projects worked in close collaboration; new features in Rust were tested out by the Servo team, and new features in Servo were used to give feedback back to the Rust team.
[src:thiserror-rust/rust-programming-language] The first version of Servo was released in 2016.
[src:thiserror-rust/rust-programming-language] The Firefox web browser shipped with Rust code as of 2016 (version 45), but components of Servo did not appear in Firefox until September 2017 (version 57) as part of the Gecko and Quantum projects.
[src:thiserror-rust/rust-programming-language] Improvements were made to the Rust toolchain ecosystem during the years following 1.0 including Rustfmt, integrated development environment integration, and a regular compiler testing and release cycle.
[src:thiserror-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust's community gained a code of conduct and an IRC chat for discussion.
[src:thiserror-rust/rust-programming-language] The earliest known adoption outside of Mozilla was by individual projects at Samsung, Facebook (now Meta Platforms), Dropbox, and Tilde, Inc., the company behind ember.js.
[src:thiserror-rust/rust-programming-language] Engineers cited performance, lack of a garbage collector, safety, and pleasantness of working in the language as reasons for the adoption.
[src:thiserror-rust/rust-programming-language] Amazon developers cited a finding by Portuguese researchers that Rust code used less energy compared to similar code written in Java.
[src:thiserror-rust/rust-programming-language] In August 2020, Mozilla laid off 250 of its 1,000 employees worldwide, as part of a corporate restructuring caused by the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:thiserror-rust/rust-programming-language] The event raised concerns about the future of Rust.
[src:thiserror-rust/rust-programming-language] In the following week, the Rust Core Team acknowledged the severe impact of the layoffs and announced that plans for a Rust foundation were underway.
[src:thiserror-rust/rust-programming-language] The first goal of the foundation would be to take ownership of all trademarks and domain names and to take financial responsibility for their costs.
[src:thiserror-rust/rust-programming-language] On February 8, 2021, the formation of the Rust Foundation was announced by five founding companies: Amazon Web Services, Google, Huawei, Microsoft, and Mozilla.
[src:thiserror-rust/rust-programming-language] The foundation would provide financial support for Rust developers in the form of grants and server funding.
