[src:thiserror-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust's ownership system consists of rules that ensure memory safety without using a garbage collector.
[src:thiserror-rust/rust-programming-language] At compile time, each value must be attached to a variable called the *owner* of that value, and every value must have exactly one owner.
[src:thiserror-rust/rust-programming-language] Values are moved between different owners through assignment or passing a value as a function parameter.
[src:thiserror-rust/rust-programming-language] Values can also be *borrowed,* meaning they are temporarily passed to a different function before being returned to the owner.
[src:thiserror-rust/rust-programming-language] Because of these ownership rules, Rust types are known as *affine types*, meaning each value may be used at most once.
[src:thiserror-rust/rust-programming-language] This enforces a form of software fault isolation as the owner of a value is solely responsible for its correctness and deallocation.
[src:thiserror-rust/rust-programming-language] When a value goes out of scope, it is *dropped* by running its destructor.
[src:thiserror-rust/rust-programming-language] The destructor may be programmatically defined through implementing the `Drop` trait.
[src:thiserror-rust/rust-programming-language] This helps manage resources such as file handles, network sockets, and locks, since when objects are dropped, the resources associated with them are closed or released automatically.
[src:thiserror-rust/rust-programming-language] Object lifetime refers to the period of time during which a reference is valid; that is, the time between the object creation and destruction.
