[src:thiserror-rust/type-system] Static type checking is the process of verifying the type safety of a program based on analysis of a program's text (source code).
[src:thiserror-rust/type-system] If a program passes a static type checker, then the program is guaranteed to satisfy some set of type safety properties for all possible inputs.
[src:thiserror-rust/type-system] Static type checking can be considered a limited form of program verification (see type safety), and in a type-safe language, can also be considered an optimization.
[src:thiserror-rust/type-system] If a compiler can prove that a program is well-typed, then it does not need to emit dynamic safety checks, allowing the resulting compiled binary to run faster and to be smaller.
[src:thiserror-rust/type-system] Static type checking for Turing-complete languages is inherently conservative.
