[src:thiserror-rust/type-system] Consequently, a static type checker will quickly detect type errors in rarely used code paths.
[src:thiserror-rust/type-system] Without static type checking, even code coverage tests with 100% coverage may be unable to find such type errors.
[src:thiserror-rust/type-system] The tests may fail to detect such type errors, because the combination of all places where values are created and all places where a certain value is used must be taken into account.
[src:thiserror-rust/type-system] A number of useful and common programming language features cannot be checked statically, such as downcasting.
[src:thiserror-rust/type-system] Thus, many languages will have both static and dynamic type checking; the static type checker verifies what it can, and dynamic checks verify the rest.
[src:thiserror-rust/type-system] Many languages with static type checking provide a way to bypass the type checker.
[src:thiserror-rust/type-system] Some languages allow programmers to choose between static and dynamic type safety.
