[src:thiserror-rust/type-system] Other languages allow writing code that is not type-safe; for example, in C, programmers can freely cast a value between any two types that have the same size, effectively subverting the type concept.
[src:thiserror-rust/type-system] Dynamic type checking is the process of verifying the type safety of a program at runtime.
[src:thiserror-rust/type-system] Implementations of dynamically type-checked languages generally associate each runtime object with a *type tag* (i.e., a reference to a type) containing its type information.
[src:thiserror-rust/type-system] This runtime type information (RTTI) can also be used to implement dynamic dispatch, late binding, downcasting, reflective programming (reflection), and similar features.
[src:thiserror-rust/type-system] Most type-safe languages include some form of dynamic type checking, even if they also have a static type checker.
[src:thiserror-rust/type-system] The reason for this is that many useful features or properties are difficult or impossible to verify statically.
[src:thiserror-rust/type-system] For example, suppose that a program defines two types, A and B, where B is a subtype of A.
[src:thiserror-rust/type-system] If the program tries to convert a value of type A to type B, which is known as downcasting, then the operation is legal only if the value being converted is actually a value of type B.
[src:thiserror-rust/type-system] Thus, a dynamic check is needed to verify that the operation is safe.
[src:thiserror-rust/type-system] This requirement is one of the criticisms of downcasting.
[src:thiserror-rust/type-system] By definition, dynamic type checking may cause a program to fail at runtime.
[src:thiserror-rust/type-system] In some programming languages, it is possible to anticipate and recover from these failures.
[src:thiserror-rust/type-system] In others, type-checking errors are considered fatal.
[src:thiserror-rust/type-system] Programming languages that include dynamic type checking but not static type checking are often called "dynamically typed programming languages".
[src:thiserror-rust/type-system] Certain languages allow both static and dynamic typing.
