[src:thiserror-rust/type-system] The term *polymorphism* refers to the ability of code (especially, functions or classes) to act on values of multiple types, or to the ability of different instances of the same data structure to contain elements of different types.
[src:thiserror-rust/type-system] Type systems that allow polymorphism generally do so to improve the potential for code re-use: in a language with polymorphism, programmers need only implement a data structure such as a list or an associative array once, rather than once for each type of element with which they plan to use it.
[src:thiserror-rust/type-system] For this reason computer scientists sometimes call the use of certain forms of polymorphism *generic programming*.
