[src:thiserror-rust/type-system] Linear types, based on the theory of linear logic, and closely related to uniqueness types, are types assigned to values having the property that they have one and only one reference to them at all times.
[src:thiserror-rust/type-system] These are valuable for describing large immutable values such as files, strings, and so on, because any operation that simultaneously destroys a linear object and creates a similar object (such as `str = str + "a"`) can be optimized "under the hood" into an in-place mutation.
[src:thiserror-rust/type-system] Normally this is not possible, as such mutations could cause side effects on parts of the program holding other references to the object, violating referential transparency.
[src:thiserror-rust/type-system] They are also used in the prototype operating system Singularity for interprocess communication, statically ensuring that processes cannot share objects in shared memory to prevent race conditions.
[src:thiserror-rust/type-system] The Clean language (a Haskell-like language) uses this type system to gain a lot of speed (compared to performing a deep copy) while remaining safe.
[src:thiserror-rust/type-system] Intersection types are types describing values that belong to *both* of two other given types with overlapping value sets.
[src:thiserror-rust/type-system] For example, in most implementations of C the signed char has range -128 to 127 and the unsigned char has range 0 to 255, so the intersection type of these two types would have range 0 to 127.
[src:thiserror-rust/type-system] Such an intersection type could be safely passed into functions expecting *either* signed or unsigned chars, because it is compatible with both types.
[src:thiserror-rust/type-system] Such a function could be passed into another function expecting an "`int` → `int`" function safely; it simply would not use the "`float` → `float`" functionality.
[src:thiserror-rust/type-system] In a subclassing hierarchy, the intersection of a type and an ancestor type (such as its parent) is the most derived type.
[src:thiserror-rust/type-system] The intersection of sibling types is empty.
[src:thiserror-rust/type-system] The Forsythe language includes a general implementation of intersection types.
[src:thiserror-rust/type-system] Union types are types describing values that belong to *either* of two types.
[src:thiserror-rust/type-system] For example, in C, the signed char has a -128 to 127 range, and the unsigned char has a 0 to 255 range, so the union of these two types would have an overall "virtual" range of -128 to 255 that may be used partially depending on which union member is accessed.
[src:thiserror-rust/type-system] Any function handling this union type would have to deal with integers in this complete range.
[src:thiserror-rust/type-system] More generally, the only valid operations on a union type are operations that are valid on *both* types being unioned.
[src:thiserror-rust/type-system] C's "union" concept is similar to union types, but is not typesafe, as it permits operations that are valid on *either* type, rather than *both*.
[src:thiserror-rust/type-system] Union types are important in program analysis, where they are used to represent symbolic values whose exact nature (e.g., value or type) is not known.
[src:thiserror-rust/type-system] In a subclassing hierarchy, the union of a type and an ancestor type (such as its parent) is the ancestor type.
[src:thiserror-rust/type-system] The union of sibling types is a subtype of their common ancestor (that is, all operations permitted on their common ancestor are permitted on the union type, but they may also have other valid operations in common).
[src:thiserror-rust/type-system] Existential types are frequently used in connection with record types to represent modules and abstract data types, due to their ability to separate implementation from interface.
[src:thiserror-rust/type-system] For example, the type "T = ∃X { a: X; f: (X → int); }" describes a module interface that has a data member named *a* of type *X* and a function named *f* that takes a parameter of the *same* type *X* and returns an integer.
[src:thiserror-rust/type-system] These types are both subtypes of the more general existential type T and correspond to concrete implementation types, so any value of one of these types is a value of type T.
[src:thiserror-rust/type-system] Given a value "t" of type "T", we know that "t.f(t.a)" is well-typed, regardless of what the abstract type *X* is.
[src:thiserror-rust/type-system] This gives flexibility for choosing types suited to a particular implementation, while clients that use only values of the interface type—the existential type—are isolated from these choices.
[src:thiserror-rust/type-system] In general it's impossible for the typechecker to infer which existential type a given module belongs to.
[src:thiserror-rust/type-system] In the above example intT { a: int; f: (int → int); } could also have the type ∃X { a: X; f: (X → int); }.
[src:thiserror-rust/type-system] Although abstract data types and modules had been implemented in programming languages for quite some time, it wasn't until 1988 that John C.
[src:thiserror-rust/type-system] Mitchell and Gordon Plotkin established the formal theory under the slogan: "Abstract [data] types have existential type".
[src:thiserror-rust/type-system] The theory is a second-order typed lambda calculus similar to System F, but with existential instead of universal quantification.
[src:thiserror-rust/type-system] In a type system with Gradual typing, variables may be assigned a type either at compile-time (which is static typing), or at runtime (which is dynamic typing).
[src:thiserror-rust/type-system] This allows software developers to choose either type paradigm as appropriate, from within a single language.
[src:thiserror-rust/type-system] Gradual typing uses a special type named *dynamic* to represent statically unknown types; gradual typing replaces the notion of type equality with a new relation called *consistency* that relates the dynamic type to every other type.
[src:thiserror-rust/type-system] The consistency relation is symmetric but not transitive.
[src:thiserror-rust/type-system] Many static type systems, such as those of C and Java, require *type declarations*: the programmer must explicitly associate each variable with a specific type.
[src:thiserror-rust/type-system] Others, such as Haskell's, perform *type inference*: the compiler draws conclusions about the types of variables based on how programmers use those variables.
[src:thiserror-rust/type-system] For example, given a function `f(x, y)` that adds `x` and `y` together, the compiler can infer that `x` and `y` must be numbers—since addition is only defined for numbers.
[src:thiserror-rust/type-system] Thus, any call to `f` elsewhere in the program that specifies a non-numeric type (such as a string or list) as an argument would signal an error.
[src:thiserror-rust/type-system] Numerical and string constants and expressions in code can and often do imply type in a particular context.
[src:thiserror-rust/type-system] For example, an expression `3.14` might imply a type of floating-point, while `[1, 2, 3]` might imply a list of integers—typically an array.
[src:thiserror-rust/type-system] Type inference is in general possible, if it is computable in the type system in question.
[src:thiserror-rust/type-system] Moreover, even if inference is not computable in general for a given type system, inference is often possible for a large subset of real-world programs.
[src:thiserror-rust/type-system] Haskell's type system, a version of Hindley–Milner, is a restriction of System Fω to so-called rank-1 polymorphic types, in which type inference is computable.
[src:thiserror-rust/type-system] Most Haskell compilers allow arbitrary-rank polymorphism as an extension, but this makes type inference not computable.
[src:thiserror-rust/type-system] A type system that assigns types to terms in type environments using typing rules is naturally associated with the decision problems of type checking, typability, and type inhabitation.
[src:thiserror-rust/type-system] Some languages like C# or Scala have a unified type system.
[src:thiserror-rust/type-system] This means that all C# types including primitive types inherit from a single root object.
[src:thiserror-rust/type-system] Every type in C# inherits from the Object class.
[src:thiserror-rust/type-system] Some languages, like Java and Raku, have a root type but also have primitive types that are not objects.
[src:thiserror-rust/type-system] Java provides wrapper object types that exist together with the primitive types so developers can use either the wrapper object types or the simpler non-object primitive types.
[src:thiserror-rust/type-system] Raku automatically converts primitive types to objects when their methods are accessed.
[src:thiserror-rust/type-system] A type checker for a statically typed language must verify that the type of any expression is consistent with the type expected by the context in which that expression appears.
[src:thiserror-rust/type-system] For example, in an assignment statement of the form `x := *e*`, the inferred type of the expression *`e`* must be consistent with the declared or inferred type of the variable `x`.
[src:thiserror-rust/type-system] This notion of consistency, called *compatibility*, is specific to each programming language.
[src:thiserror-rust/type-system] If the type of *`e`* and the type of `x` are the same, and assignment is allowed for that type, then this is a valid expression.
[src:thiserror-rust/type-system] Thus, in the simplest type systems, the question of whether two types are compatible reduces to that of whether they are *equal* (or *equivalent*).
[src:thiserror-rust/type-system] Different languages, however, have different criteria for when two type expressions are understood to denote the same type.
[src:thiserror-rust/type-system] In languages with subtyping, the compatibility relation is more complex: If `B` is a subtype of `A`, then a value of type `B` can be used in a context where one of type `A` is expected (covariant), even if the reverse is not true.
[src:thiserror-rust/type-system] Like equivalence, the subtype relation is defined differently for each programming language, with many variations possible.
[src:thiserror-rust/type-system] The presence of parametric or ad hoc polymorphism in a language may also have implications for type compatibility.
